## Summary

Adds `channels.discord.apiTimeoutMs` to the Discord channel config surface and threads it into Discord REST request-client construction.

Default behavior stays at `15000` ms. Configured values are accepted at both `channels.discord.apiTimeoutMs` and `channels.discord.accounts.<accountId>.apiTimeoutMs`, capped at `120000` ms by the schema.

This also completes the public config surface for the new key:

- regenerated bundled channel config metadata
- refreshed config docs baseline hash
- added Discord docs and config UI hints
- added focused schema/runtime tests for default, configured, per-account, invalid, and proxied timeout behavior

Related to #85745.

## Real behavior proof

Behavior addressed: Discord REST API timeout is now configurable through `channels.discord.apiTimeoutMs` and per-account overrides without changing the default timeout when unset.

Real environment tested: Local OpenClaw checkout on macOS, using the real Discord `createDiscordRestClient` and `RequestClient` code path against a local slow HTTP endpoint. No Discord token was available in this environment, so live Discord network proof was not run.

Exact steps or command run after this patch:

```bash
node --import tsx <<'NODE'
import http from "node:http";
import { performance } from "node:perf_hooks";
import { createDiscordRestClient } from "./extensions/discord/src/client.ts";

const requests = [];
const server = http.createServer((req, res) => {
  requests.push(req.url ?? "");
  setTimeout(() => {
    res.setHeader("Content-Type", "application/json");
    res.end(JSON.stringify({ ok: true }));
  }, 1_000);
});

await new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
  server.once("error", reject);
  server.listen(0, "127.0.0.1", () => resolve());
});

const address = server.address();
const baseUrl = `http://127.0.0.1:${address.port}/api`;

const defaultClient = createDiscordRestClient({
  cfg: { channels: { discord: { token: "Bot redacted-test-token" } } },
});
const configuredClient = createDiscordRestClient({
  cfg: { channels: { discord: { token: "Bot redacted-test-token", apiTimeoutMs: 25 } } },
});
const accountClient = createDiscordRestClient({
  accountId: "ops",
  cfg: {
    channels: {
      discord: {
        apiTimeoutMs: 40,
        accounts: { ops: { token: "Bot redacted-ops-token", apiTimeoutMs: 25 } },
      },
    },
  },
});

configuredClient.rest.options.baseUrl = baseUrl;
configuredClient.rest.options.queueRequests = false;

const started = performance.now();
let observed = "none";
try {
  await configuredClient.rest.get("/users/@me");
  observed = "completed";
} catch (error) {
  observed = error instanceof DOMException ? error.name : error instanceof Error ? error.name : typeof error;
} finally {
  server.close();
}

console.log(`defaultTimeoutMs=${defaultClient.rest.options.timeout}`);
console.log(`configuredTimeoutMs=${configuredClient.rest.options.timeout}`);
console.log(`accountTimeoutMs=${accountClient.rest.options.timeout}`);
console.log(`observedResult=${observed}`);
console.log(`elapsedMs=${Math.round(performance.now() - started)}`);
console.log(`requestPath=${requests[0] ?? "missing"}`);
NODE
```

Evidence after fix:

```text
defaultTimeoutMs=15000
configuredTimeoutMs=25
accountTimeoutMs=25
observedResult=AbortError
elapsedMs=29
requestPath=/api/v10/users/@me
```

Observed result after fix: the unset client keeps the 15 second default, configured top-level and per-account clients use the configured 25 ms timeout, and the real REST request path aborts around the configured timeout instead of waiting for the 1 second local endpoint response.

What was not tested: live Discord API behavior against a real large guild, because this local environment does not have a Discord bot token configured.

